<p>Bordeaux reds reveal themselves in layers. <strong>Primary aromas</strong> showcase dark fruits—blackcurrant from Cabernet Sauvignon, plum and cherry from Merlot, with Cabernet Franc contributing violet and bell pepper notes. <strong>Secondary aromatics</strong> from fermentation and élevage include vanilla, cedar, and tobacco from French oak aging, plus earthy graphite minerality from Left Bank gravelly soils.</p>

<p>With bottle age, <strong>tertiary complexity</strong> emerges: leather, forest floor, truffle, dried herbs, and the distinctive "pencil shavings" note prized in mature Pauillac wines. White Bordeaux offers citrus zest, white flowers, and honey, with noble rot dessert wines adding apricot, orange marmalade, and exotic spice complexity.</p>

