<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Left Bank vs Right Bank Temperature Rules</strong> - Left Bank Bordeaux (Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant from Médoc, Haut-Médoc, Saint-Julien, Pauillac, Saint-Estèphe, and Margaux) should be served at 64-66°F to showcase their structured tannins and cassis notes. Right Bank wines (Merlot-dominant from Saint-Émilion and Pomerol) are best at 62-64°F to preserve their softer, plum-forward character and silky texture.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Bordeaux's Vintage Chart for Strategic Decanting</strong> - Great vintage Bordeaux (like 2005, 2009, 2010, 2016) from top châteaux need 2-4 hours of decanting even when mature, while difficult vintages (2013, 2007, 2002) often drink better with just 30-60 minutes to avoid over-exposure. Young Bordeaux under 10 years old always benefits from aggressive decanting to soften those firm Cabernet Sauvignon tannins.</li>

  <li><strong>Invest in Proper Bordeaux Glassware Proportions</strong> - Traditional Bordeaux glasses have a taller, narrower bowl than Burgundy glasses to concentrate the wine's cedar, tobacco, and dark fruit aromatics while managing the higher alcohol levels. The rim should curve slightly inward to capture the complex bouquet that develops in aged Bordeaux wines, especially those secondary leather and earthy notes from bottle aging.</li>

  <li><strong>Follow the 20-Year Rule for Classified Growth Aging</strong> - Bordeaux First Growths (Lafite, Latour, Margaux, Mouton, Haut-Brion) typically need 15-20 years to reach peak drinking, while Second and Third Growths are often optimal at 10-15 years. Cru Bourgeois wines are designed for 5-10 years of aging. The key indicator is when the wine's graphite minerality begins to emerge alongside the fruit.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Bordeaux Drinking Windows Precisely</strong> - Most classified growth Bordeaux have two optimal drinking periods: an early "fruit window" at 8-12 years when primary flavors dominate, and a mature "tertiary window" at 18-25 years when complex earthy, truffle, and tobacco notes develop. Avoid the "dumb period" between years 12-18 when many Bordeaux temporarily shut down.</li>

  <li><strong>Read Bordeaux Labels for Blend Intelligence</strong> - Look for the phrase "Mis en bouteille au château" to ensure estate bottling. The alcohol level tells a story: 13-13.5% suggests a cooler vintage with more elegance, while 14%+ indicates a warmer year with riper fruit. Many top châteaux now list harvest dates on back labels - earlier harvests (mid-September) often mean more finesse.</li>

  <li><strong>Master the Bordeaux Food Pairing Triangle</strong> - Left Bank Bordeaux pairs classically with lamb and beef due to the Cabernet Sauvignon's firm tannins that cut through fat, while Right Bank wines complement duck, game birds, and mushroom dishes that echo their earthier Merlot character. Both styles excel with aged hard cheeses that match their development timeline.</li>

  <li><strong>Storage Position Matters for Bordeaux Corks</strong> - Bordeaux bottles should be stored at a 15-degree angle rather than completely horizontal to keep corks moist while preventing sediment from settling against the cork. This is especially crucial for Bordeaux over 15 years old, as their traditional long corks can dry out and allow premature oxidation of these age-worthy wines.</li>
</ol>





  <h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Bordeaux wines showcase exceptional aging potential, with quality levels determining longevity. <strong>Grand Cru Classé wines</strong> from prestigious châteaux like Lafite-Rothschild or Margaux can evolve beautifully for 30-50 years, while <strong>Cru Bourgeois</strong> typically peaks within 10-15 years. Basic Bordeaux AOC wines are best consumed within 3-5 years to preserve their fresh fruit character.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Right Bank Merlot-dominant wines from Saint-Émilion and Pomerol generally reach maturity earlier (8-20 years) due to softer tannins, while Left Bank Cabernet Sauvignon-based wines from Médoc need 15-30 years to fully integrate their robust structure. <strong>Sweet Sauternes</strong> can age gracefully for decades, with top estates like d'Yquem remaining vibrant after 50+ years.</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Bottle</h3>
<p>During aging, Bordeaux undergoes remarkable transformation. Initial bold tannins from Cabernet Sauvignon gradually polymerize and soften, while primary blackcurrant and plum flavors evolve into complex <strong>tertiary aromas</strong>: leather, tobacco, cedar, truffle, and graphite. The wine's color transitions from deep purple to brick-red, indicating phenolic development.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage Conditions</h3>
<ul class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
<li><strong>Temperature:</strong> Consistent 55-58°F (13-14°C)</li>
<li><strong>Humidity:</strong> 70-75% to prevent cork drying</li>
<li><strong>Position:</strong> Horizontal storage keeps corks moist</li>
<li><strong>Darkness:</strong> UV protection prevents premature aging</li>
</ul>

<h3>Aging vs Spoilage Signs</h3>
<p><strong>Proper aging</strong> shows: brick-red color, integrated tannins, complex bouquet, and clear liquid. <strong>Warning signs</strong> include: vinegar aromas (acetic acid), mushroom odors (cork taint), or excessive browning indicating oxidation. Well-aged Bordeaux should maintain fruit balance despite evolutionary changes, never becoming thin or sharp.</p>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

