<p>Young Bordeaux displays primary fruit flavors—blackcurrant, plum, and cedar—alongside firm tannins. <strong>Over time, these tannins polymerize</strong>, creating silky textures while developing secondary aromas of tobacco, leather, and forest floor. The fruit transitions from bright to dried characteristics, gaining tertiary complexity like truffle, graphite, and savory herbs.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>
