<h3>Aging Assessment</h3>
<p>Properly aged Bordeaux develops <strong>brick-red color at the rim</strong> while maintaining deep core color. The wine should pour clear without sediment clouds. Aromas become more complex but remain fresh—avoid bottles showing excessive browning, vinegar notes, or musty cork taint. Well-cellared wines reveal layered complexity with each sip, balancing fruit, earth, and structural elements harmoniously.</p>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Bordeaux wines are among the world's most age-worthy reds, with proper cellaring transforming their character dramatically over decades. Understanding when and how to age these wines maximizes their potential.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Classification</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>First Growth Châteaux</strong> (Lafite, Latour, Margaux): 30-50+ years from great vintages</li>
<li><strong>Classified Growths</strong>: 15-30 years depending on vintage and producer</li>
