<li><strong>White Bordeaux</strong>: Sauternes can age 20-50+ years; dry whites 5-15 years</li>
</ul>

<h3>Evolution During Aging</h3>
<p>Young Bordeaux displays intense primary fruit flavors—blackcurrant, plum, and violet—supported by firm tannins from Cabernet Sauvignon and oak aging. As wines mature, these aggressive tannins polymerize and soften, while primary fruit evolves into complex secondary notes of leather, tobacco, cedar, and earthy minerality. The wine's color shifts from deep purple to brick-red hues, particularly at the rim.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most classified Bordeaux enter their first drinking window 8-12 years after vintage, when tannins begin integrating. Premium estates often show two peaks: an early plateau at 10-15 years, then a mature phase at 20-30 years when tertiary complexity fully develops.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store bottles horizontally at 55-58°F with 70% humidity and minimal vibration. Bordeaux's traditional heavy glass and long corks make them particularly suitable for extended cellaring. Avoid temperature fluctuations above 5°F.</p>

<h3>Monitoring Wine Health</h3>
<p>Properly aged Bordeaux shows clear color with natural sediment, maintained fruit integration, and evolved aromatics. Warning signs include browning at a young age, volatile acidity (vinegar notes), or complete fruit loss indicating oxidation or storage problems.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Left Bank and Right Bank Bordeaux?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Left Bank Bordeaux (Médoc, Haut-Médoc) is predominantly Cabernet Sauvignon-based with more structured, tannic wines from gravel soils, while Right Bank (Saint-Émilion, Pomerol) features Merlot-dominant blends that are softer and more approachable from clay and limestone soils. Left Bank wines typically require longer aging and pair better with red meat, whereas Right Bank wines are more versatile with food and accessible when young.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Bordeaux wine good for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Right Bank Bordeaux wines like Saint-Émilion and Pomerol are excellent for beginners due to their Merlot-dominant blends that offer softer tannins and approachable fruit flavors. Start with Bordeaux Supérieur or entry-level château wines rather than classified growths, as they're more affordable and ready to drink. Left Bank wines can be challenging for newcomers due to their firm tannins and need for decanting or aging.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I age Bordeaux wine before drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Bordeaux wines benefit from 5-15 years of aging, with classified growths often needing 10-20 years to reach peak maturity. Entry-level Bordeaux and Bordeaux Supérieur can be enjoyed within 2-5 years, while prestigious châteaux like Lafite or Margaux may require decades to fully develop. The vintage quality and storage conditions significantly impact aging potential—great vintages like 2010 or 2016 will age longer than lighter years.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value in Bordeaux wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cru Bourgeois wines from the Médoc offer exceptional value, providing quality comparable to classified growths at a fraction of the price. Look for châteaux like Sociando-Mallet, Haut-Marbuzet, or Phélan Ségur for reliable quality under $50. Saint-Émilion Grand Cru wines also provide excellent value, as the classification includes many producers offering great quality-to-price ratios compared to the Left Bank's inflated classified growth prices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Bordeaux wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Bordeaux red wines at 60-65°F (15-18°C), which is slightly cooler than room temperature to preserve the wine's structure and prevent alcohol from overwhelming the palate. Young, tannic Bordeaux benefits from the cooler end of this range, while mature wines can be served slightly warmer to enhance their complex aromatics. Always decant older Bordeaux (10+ years) for 1-2 hours before serving to allow proper aeration and sediment separation.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the most common mistakes when buying Bordeaux?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is buying classified growth wines too young and expecting them to be ready to drink—these wines need significant aging time. Many buyers also overlook excellent value producers in favor of famous names, missing opportunities with Cru Bourgeois and lesser-known châteaux that offer similar quality. Additionally, purchasing wines from poor vintages without research can lead to disappointment, as Bordeaux quality varies dramatically between years.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Bordeaux but more affordable?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Cabernet Sauvignon-Merlot blends from Washington State's Columbia Valley or Virginia's Piedmont region, which offer similar structure and complexity at lower prices. Languedoc wines from southern France, particularly those labeled "Bordeaux blend" or featuring Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot, provide excellent alternatives with similar terroir influences. Australian blends from Margaret River and some Tuscan Super Tuscans also mirror Bordeaux's style while offering better value and earlier drinkability.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I know if my Bordeaux wine has gone bad?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Signs of a faulty Bordeaux include a musty, wet cardboard smell (cork taint), vinegar-like aromas (acetification), or a brownish color in young wines indicating premature oxidation. Sediment is normal in aged Bordeaux, but if accompanied by off-odors or a flat taste, the wine may be past its prime. Trust your nose first—a healthy Bordeaux should smell of dark fruits, earth, and spices, not barnyard, nail polish remover, or excessive alcohol heat.</p>
  </div>
